				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">pets ability to push mob can be as much as 20 times greater than any PC melee class.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Then why is it if I'm soloing with my pet in the rogue position, I never have to back up more than a couple of feet even when the warder is hitting more often than I do?
<br />

<br />
The whole premise of this rant is based on popular myth, it simply doesn't hold up to experience.  The only reason pets appear to push harder than players is that when they do push something back, they instantly close the gap - players usually don't.  In my experience, a similarly hasted monk or ranger pushes about as much as a quadding pet.  (And I've done a ton of testing on it, after seeing similar claims in places like the monk boards - but then, I don't expect non-pet classes to know better.)
<br />

<br />
Even if all this were true, how would it mean pet classes were broken? I don't get it.
<br />

